# Testing Python

> **DRAFT — starter content generated to satisfy CLAUDE.md's always-apply
> contract. Review and customize. Extends CLAUDE.md Rule 8 (Tests verify
> intent, not just behavior).**

## Structure

- Tests live in `tests/` mirroring `src/slh/` (`tests/test_<module>.py`).
- One concern per file. Don't bundle web tests with curriculum tests.
- Use `pytest` only. No `unittest`-style classes unless interop forces it.

## Names encode intent

A test name is a sentence: `test_<subject>_<expected_behavior>_<condition>`.
- ✅ `test_v1_accepts_shallow_compliance`
- ✅ `test_persona_pairs_differ_in_at_least_three_dimensions`
- ❌ `test_v1_method_1`
- ❌ `test_check_works`

If the test name doesn't read as a claim about the system, the test is testing
the wrong thing.

## Fixtures

- Function-scoped by default. Module/session scope only when setup is
  genuinely expensive AND the test order doesn't matter.
- Mutating module-scoped fixtures (env, caches, file system) MUST restore
  on teardown. Use `pytest.MonkeyPatch()` with `mp.undo()`, not raw
  `os.environ[...] = ...`.
- Fixture names describe what they provide, not how:
  - ✅ `client` (returns a TestClient)
  - ❌ `setup_client_and_clear_cache`

## Assertions

- One claim per test. If you need multiple `assert`s, they should all be
  describing facets of the same claim.
- Assertion failure messages are part of the test — name what was expected
  vs. observed when not obvious from the values: `assert x == 3, f"expected
  3 deltas, got {x}"`.
- Don't assert "everything looks fine" by counting checks (`assert
  passed == total`). That couples the test to every gate elsewhere and
  noise propagates. Assert the structural shape you care about.

## Coverage

- `pytest --cov=slh --cov-fail-under=85` is enforced in `pyproject.toml`.
- 100% coverage is not a goal; covered-and-meaningful is. A line covered by a
  test that doesn't assert on it is not really covered.
- Add `# pragma: no cover` to unreachable / launcher / `__main__` blocks; do
  not add it to silence a missing test.

## Golden sets

- Golden expectations live in `slh/goldenset.py` as a typed structure, not
  scattered as inline asserts.
- Each expectation has a `rationale` field naming the intent it pins. A check
  with no rationale is a check waiting to flake.
- Per-persona / per-dimension scope expectations use the `persona` field on
  `MetricExpectation` rather than inventing parallel data structures.
- Add a gate when you add a behavior, not later. The gate is the proof the
  behavior persists.

## Determinism

- Seeded RNG everywhere; never `random.random()` without a seed.
- `Date.now()` / `time.time()` calls in tests must be frozen or mocked.
- Floating-point assertions use `pytest.approx(...)` with an explicit
  tolerance, not bare `==`.

## What NOT to test

- Don't test third-party libraries.
- Don't test getters/setters or `__init__` boilerplate.
- Don't test logging output unless logging IS the contract.
- Don't write a test that fails when behavior is right but cosmetic phrasing
  changes (asserting on substring presence is OK; asserting on exact byte
  count is brittle).
